  "prompt": "Knighthood: Is it possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted, but the process and the title received differ. Here's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Honorary Knighthood:** Non-British citizens are usually awarded **honorary knighthoods or damehoods**. Because they are not citizens of the UK or a Commonwealth realm where the British monarch is Head of State, they cannot formally be made a Knight Commander (KBE) or Dame Commander (DBE) in the Order of the British Empire. Instead, they receive the award in an honorary capacity.\n\n*   **Using the Title:** Recipients of honorary knighthoods/damehoods **cannot use the title \"Sir\" or \"Dame\" before their name.** However, they can use the post-nominal letters (e.g., KBE or DBE) after their name.\n\n*   **Naturalization:** If a person who has received an honorary knighthood/damehood later becomes a British citizen, the award can be converted into a substantive knighthood/damehood, and they would then be entitled to use the title \"Sir\" or \"Dame.\"\n\n**In summary:** A non-British citizen can be \"knighted\" in the honorary sense, but they don't get to use the title \"Sir\" or \"Dame\" unless they later become a British citizen and have the award converted.",
